{"title_page": "Roger Fieldhouse", "text_new": "'''Roger Fieldhouse''' (1940\u20132020) was a British historian and academic. He was Professor of Adult Education at the [[University of Exeter]] between 1986 and 1996.\n\nFieldhouse was born in [[East Sheen]] to Ernest Fieldhouse, a commercial traveller, and Phyllis, ''n\u00e9e'' Scott. He studied at history at the [[University of Reading]] between 1960 and 1963. In the mid-1960s, he became a tutor-organiser for the [[Workers' Educational Association]] in [[North Yorkshire]]; there he worked with local people to explore the area's history. In 1970, he was appointed to the department of adult education and extramural studies at the [[University of Leeds]], and later secured promotion to a [[Senior lecturer|senior lectureship]] and to be head of department. He studied part-time for a [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate]] at Leeds;<ref name=\"guardian\">Dick Taylor, [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/apr/02/roger-fieldhouse-obituary \"Roger Fieldhouse obituary\"], ''The Guardian'', 2 April 2020. Retrieved 14 April 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.uall.ac.uk/posts/in-memoriam \"In Memoriam\"], ''The Universities Association for Lifelong Learning'', 12 February 2020. Retrieved 14 April 2020.</ref> his PhD was awarded in 1984 for his [[thesis]] \"The ideology of English responsible body adult education 1925\u20131950\".<ref>[https://leeds.primo.exlibrisgroup.com/permalink/44LEE_INST/13rlbcs/alma991008846589705181 \"The ideology of English responsible body adult education 1925\u20131950\"], ''University of Leeds Library''. Retrieved 14 April 2020.</ref> In 1986, he moved to the [[University of Exeter]] to take up the chair in adult education; he remained there until he retired in 1996.<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\nIn the view of the historian [[Richard Taylor (historian)|Richard Taylor]], Fieldhouse's work had \"contributed significantly to two academic fields: local history; and the history and philosophy of modern British adult education\".<ref name=\"guardian\"/> In the former vein, he authored ''A History of Swaledale and Richmond'' (1978); in the latter, he authored ''A History of Modern British Adult Education'' (1996). He also wrote ''Anti-apartheid: A History of the Movement in Britain'' (2005) and, with Taylor, co-edited ''E. P. Thompson and English Radicalism'' (2013).<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Exeter]]\n", "text_old": "'''Roger Fieldhouse''' (1940\u20132020) was a British historian and academic. He was Professor of Adult Education at the [[University of Exeter]] between 1986 and 1996.\n\nFieldhouse was born in [[East Sheen]] to Ernest Fieldhouse, a commercial traveller, and Phyllis, ''n\u00e9e'' Scott. He studied at history at the [[University of Reading]] between 1960 and 1963. In the mid-1960s, he became a tutor-organiser for the [[Workers' Educational Association]] in [[North Yorkshire]]; there he worked with local people to explore the area's history. In 1970, he was appointed to the department of adult education and extramural studies at the [[University of Leeds]], and later secured promotion to a [[Senior lecturer|senior lectureship]] and to be head of department. He studied part-time for a [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate]] at Leeds;<ref name=\"guardian\">Dick Taylor, [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/apr/02/roger-fieldhouse-obituary \"Roger Fieldhouse obituary\"], ''The Guardian'', 2 April 2020. Retrieved 14 April 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.uall.ac.uk/posts/in-memoriam \"In Memoriam\"], ''The Universities Association for Lifelong Learning'', 12 February 2020. Retrieved 14 April 2020.</ref> his PhD was awarded in 1984 for his [[thesis]] \"The ideology of English responsible body adult education 1925\u20131950\".<ref>[https://leeds.primo.exlibrisgroup.com/permalink/44LEE_INST/13rlbcs/alma991008846589705181 \"The ideology of English responsible body adult education 1925\u20131950\"], ''University of Leeds Library''. Retrieved 14 April 2020.</ref> In 1986, he moved to the [[University of Exeter]] to take up the chair in adult education; he remained there until he retired in 1996.<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\nIn the view of the historian [[Dick Taylor (historian)|Dick Taylor]], Fieldhouse's work had \"contributed significantly to two academic fields: local history; and the history and philosophy of modern British adult education\".<ref name=\"guardian\"/> In the former vein, he authored ''A History of Swaledale and Richmond'' (1978); in the latter, he authored ''A History of Modern British Adult Education'' (1996). He also wrote ''Anti-apartheid: A History of the Movement in Britain'' (2005) and, with Taylor, co-edited ''E. P. Thompson and English Radicalism'' (2013).<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Exeter]]\n", "name_user": "Kallemax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Dick -> Richard, this seems to be his proper/professional name, e.g. https://www.theguardian.com/profile/richard-taylor / https://www.wolfson.cam.ac.uk/people/fellows/emeritus-fellows - I guess he only signed the obit \"Dick\" as a final friendly gesture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Fieldhouse"}
{"title_page": "Melanie Scrofano", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019|cs1-dates=ly}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Melanie Scrofano\n| image       = Melanie Scrofano 2016.jpg\n| caption     = Scrofano in 2016\n| birth_name  = Melanie Neige Scrofano<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/Melanie-Neige-Scrofano-292448954852/ |title=Melanie Neige Scrofano |website=Facebook.com |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = <!-- Do NOT add without appropriate [[WP:Reliable sources]] - IMDb does NOT count -->\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation  = Actress\n| partner     = \n| children    = 2\n| website     = \n| years_active = 2002\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Melanie Neige Scrofano''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] actress. She is known for playing the roles of Rebecca on the [[CBC Television|CBC]] [[dramedy]] series ''[[Being Erica]]'', October on the [[Showcase (Canadian TV channel)|Showcase]] comedy [[mockumentary]] series ''[[Pure Pwnage]]'', and Tia on the [[CTV Television Network]] fantasy drama series ''[[The Listener (TV series)|The Listener]]''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Andrew Ryan |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/seven-days-of-television-may-26-to-june-1/article18819671/ |title=Seven Days of Television: May 26 to June 1 [1 of 7] |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=May 26, 2014 |accessdate=2016-05-29}}</ref> Scrofano has played the lead role on [[Syfy]]'s modern Western drama ''[[Wynonna Earp (TV series)|Wynonna Earp]]'' since 2016.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lesley Goldberg |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/syfy-acquires-comic-book-adaptation-810544 |title=Syfy Acquires Comic Book Adaptation 'Wynonna Earp' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 22, 2015 |accessdate=2016-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Nellie Andreeva |url=https://deadline.com/2015/07/syfy-wynonna-earp-series-cast-melanie-scrofano-1201483399/ |title=Syfy Acquires \u2018Wynonna Earp\u2019 Series; Melanie Scrofano To Star |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 22, 2015 |accessdate=2016-05-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nScrofano grew up in [[Ottawa]], Ontario.<ref>{{cite news |author=Eric Volmers |url=https://calgaryherald.com/entertainment/television/calgary-shot-wynonna-earp-ready-to-action |title=Calgary-shot Wynonna Earp ready for action |work=[[Calgary Herald]] |date=March 31, 2016 |accessdate=2016-05-29 }}</ref> Her father is an engineer and her mother is a government worker. She is of Italian and French-Canadian descent. She began modeling at the age of 13, and picked up acting when her agent began submitting her for acting jobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.panoramitalia.com/en/arts-culture/music/lives-melanie-scrofano/1283/|title=The many lives of  Melanie Scrofano - Panoram Italia|last=Imagiamedia.ca|website=www.panoramitalia.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-27}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed in a July 2017 ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' article that Scrofano was pregnant for the duration of filming the second season of ''[[Wynonna Earp (TV series)|Wynonna Earp]]''. She gave birth to a son in April 2017, shortly after production on the series had wrapped.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/features/wynonna-earp-emily-andras-melanie-scrofano-news-exclusive-1202476757/|title=\u2018Wynonna Earp\u2019 Exclusive: Showrunner Emily Andras and Star Melanie Scrofano Break Down That Big Reveal|author=Maureen Ryan|date=July 8, 2017|work=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://calgaryherald.com/entertainment/television/no-pregnant-pause-expecting-a-baby-didnt-slow-down-wynonna-earp-or-the-actress-playing-her|title=\u2018No pregnant pause: Expecting a baby didn't slow down Wynonna Earp or the actress playing her|author=Eric Volmers|date=August 4, 2017|work=Calgary Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-19}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable so